==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ptarmigan
<hw>Ptar"mi*gan</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gael.
<ets>tarmachan</ets>; cf. Ir. <ets>tarmochan</ets>,
<ets>tarmonach</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any grouse of the
genus <gen>Lagopus</gen>, of which numerous species are known. The feet
are completely feathered. Most of the species are brown in summer, but
turn white, or nearly white, in winter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ They chiefly inhabit the northern countries and high
mountains of Europe, Asia, and America. The common European species is
<spn>Lagopus mutus</spn>. The Scotch grouse, red grouse, or moor fowl
(<spn>Lagopus Scoticus</spn>), is reddish brown, and does not turn white
in winter. The white, or willow, ptarmigan (<spn>Lagopus albus</spn>) is
found in both Europe and America.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ptenoglossa</ent>⟦br⟧
